xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>14142</fr:anchor><fr:addr>jms-0051</fr:addr><fr:route>jms-0051.xml</fr:route><fr:title>An alternative definition of duploids</fr:title><fr:taxon>Observation</fr:taxon><fr:date><fr:year>2023</fr:year><fr:month>4</fr:month><fr:day>15</fr:day></fr:date><fr:authors><fr:author><fr:link
type="local"
href="jonmsterling.xml"
addr="jonmsterling"
title="Jon Sterling">Jon Sterling</fr:link></fr:author></fr:authors></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p>Equivalently, we can define a <fr:link
type="local"
href="jms-0050.xml"
addr="jms-0050"
title="Duploid">duploid</fr:link> to be a <fr:link
type="local"
href="jms-004T.xml"
addr="jms-004T"
title="Univalent deductive system">univalent</fr:link> <fr:link
type="local"
href="jms-004F.xml"
addr="jms-004F"
title="Preduploid">preduploid</fr:link> such that every object is <fr:em>merely equipped with</fr:em> both an <fr:link
type="local"
href="jms-004M.xml"
addr="jms-004M"
title="Upshift structure">upshift</fr:link> and a <fr:link
type="local"
href="jms-004P.xml"
addr="jms-004P"
title="Downshift structure">downshift</fr:link>.</fr:p><fr:p>To see that the <fr:link
type="local"
href="jms-0050.xml"
addr="jms-0050"
title="Duploid">main definition</fr:link> implies our alternative definition, let <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex> be an object of the preduploid; because we are proving that <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex> is <fr:em>merely equipped with</fr:em> both an <fr:link
type="local"
href="jms-004M.xml"
addr="jms-004M"
title="Upshift structure">upshift</fr:link> and a <fr:link
type="local"
href="jms-004P.xml"
addr="jms-004P"
title="Downshift structure">downshift</fr:link>, we may proceed by cases on the <fr:link
type="local"
href="jms-0045.xml"
addr="jms-0045"
title="Polarized object">polarization</fr:link> of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p><fr:ol><fr:li>If <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex> is <fr:link
type="local"
href="jms-004B.xml"
addr="jms-004B"
title="Positive and negative objects">positive</fr:link>, we choose the identity map <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[A\vdash  A]]></fr:tex> for the downshift and we use our assumption to deduce that <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex> has an upshift.</fr:li>
  <fr:li>If <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex> is <fr:link
type="local"
href="jms-004B.xml"
addr="jms-004B"
title="Positive and negative objects">negative</fr:link>, we choose the identity map <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[A\vdash  A]]></fr:tex> for the upshift and we use our assumption to deduce that <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex> has a downshift.</fr:li></fr:ol>
 
   
   <fr:tree
toc="false"
numbered="true"
show-heading="true"
show-metadata="false"
expanded="true"
root="false"
xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>13250</fr:anchor><fr:addr>#465</fr:addr><fr:route>unstable-465.xml</fr:route><fr:taxon>Proof</fr:taxon><fr:date><fr:year>2023</fr:year><fr:month>4</fr:month><fr:day>15</fr:day></fr:date><fr:authors><fr:author><fr:link
type="local"
href="jonmsterling.xml"
addr="jonmsterling"
title="Jon Sterling">Jon Sterling</fr:link></fr:author></fr:authors><fr:parent>jms-0051</fr:parent></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter>
  <fr:p>Conversely, assume that every object is merely equipped with both an upshift and a downshift. That a positive object <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[P]]></fr:tex> has an upshift <fr:link
type="local"
href="jms-004X.xml"
addr="jms-004X"
title="Uniqueness of upshifts">is a proposition</fr:link>, so we can use our assumption that <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[P]]></fr:tex> <fr:em>merely</fr:em> has an upshift. That a negative object <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[N]]></fr:tex> has a downshift <fr:link
type="local"
href="jms-004Z.xml"
addr="jms-004Z"
title="Uniqueness of downshifts">is likewise a proposition</fr:link>, so we can use our assumption that <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[N]]></fr:tex> <fr:em>merely</fr:em> has a downshift.</fr:p>
</fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree>
 
</fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree><fr:tree
toc="true"
numbered="false"
show-heading="true"
show-metadata="true"
expanded="false"
root="false"
xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>14144</fr:anchor><fr:addr>jms-004X</fr:addr><fr:route>jms-004X.xml</fr:route><fr:title>Uniqueness of upshifts</fr:title><fr:taxon>Lemma</fr:taxon><fr:date><fr:year>2023</fr:year><fr:month>4</fr:month><fr:day>15</fr:day></fr:date><fr:authors><fr:author><fr:link
type="local"
href="jonmsterling.xml"
addr="jonmsterling"
title="Jon Sterling">Jon Sterling</fr:link></fr:author></fr:authors></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p>Let <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[P\in \mathcal {D}]]></fr:tex> be a <fr:link
type="local"
href="jms-004B.xml"
addr="jms-004B"
title="Positive and negative objects">positive</fr:link> object in a <fr:link
type="local"
href="jms-004S.xml"
addr="jms-004S"
title="Negatively univalent deductive system">negatively univalent deductive system</fr:link>; then the type of <fr:link
type="local"
href="jms-004M.xml"
addr="jms-004M"
title="Upshift structure">upshift structures</fr:link> on <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[P]]></fr:tex> is a proposition. In this case, we may refer to the property of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[P]]></fr:tex> <fr:em>having an upshift</fr:em>.</fr:p>
 
   
   <fr:tree
toc="false"
numbered="true"
show-heading="true"
show-metadata="false"
expanded="true"
root="false"
xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>13234</fr:anchor><fr:addr>#487</fr:addr><fr:route>unstable-487.xml</fr:route><fr:taxon>Proof</fr:taxon><fr:date><fr:year>2023</fr:year><fr:month>4</fr:month><fr:day>15</fr:day></fr:date><fr:authors><fr:author><fr:link
type="local"
href="jonmsterling.xml"
addr="jonmsterling"
title="Jon Sterling">Jon Sterling</fr:link></fr:author></fr:authors><fr:parent>jms-004X</fr:parent></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter>
  <fr:p>Let <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[f_0:M_0\vdash  P]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[f_1:M_1\vdash  P]]></fr:tex> be two <fr:link
type="local"
href="jms-004M.xml"
addr="jms-004M"
title="Upshift structure">upshift structures</fr:link> on <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[P]]></fr:tex>, whose inverse delay maps are written <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[d_0,d_1]]></fr:tex> respectively. We wish to identify the pairs <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[{\mathopen {}\left (M_0,f_0\right )\mathclose {}}]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[{\mathopen {}\left (M_1,f_1\right )\mathclose {}}]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>

  <fr:p>All four maps <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[f_0,f_1,d_0,d_1]]></fr:tex> are linear: the forcing maps are linear by definition, and the delay maps are linear because they come from a positive object. Thus we have a linearly invertible linear map <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[f_1;d_0 : M_1\vdash  M_0]]></fr:tex>; because <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathcal {D}]]></fr:tex> is assumed <fr:link
type="local"
href="jms-004S.xml"
addr="jms-004S"
title="Negatively univalent deductive system">negatively univalent</fr:link>, we may identify the pairs <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[{\mathopen {}\left (M_0,1_{M_0} : M_0\vdash  M_0\right )\mathclose {}}]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[{\mathopen {}\left (M_1,{\mathopen {}\left (f_1;d_0 : M_1\vdash  M_0\right )\mathclose {}}\right )\mathclose {}}]]></fr:tex>. Precomposing with <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[f_0 : M_0\vdash  P]]></fr:tex> in both sides, we have <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[{\mathopen {}\left (M_0,f_0\right )\mathclose {}} = {\mathopen {}\left (M_1,f_1\right )\mathclose {}}]]></fr:tex> because <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[d_0]]></fr:tex> is linear as a map out of a positive object.</fr:p>
</fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree>
 
